$lang['How do you decode Hexadecimal?'] = 'Hexadecimal hi engtin nge i decode ang?';
$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'Hexadecimal decode chungchang sawi dawn chuan hriat tur tlemte a awm. Pakhatnaah chuan decimal system ang bawkin hexadecimal system hian number entîrtu symbol 10 (0-9) a nei a. Mahse, hexadecimal-ah chuan heng digit te hian decimal system-a an digit-te aiin a let hnih zetin value an nei a. Chuvangin, number “10” chu hexadecimal-a symbol “A” hmanga entir a nih laiin, decimal system-ah chuan “10” nen a inang ang.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'Chutiang bawkin Hexadecimal (“F” hmanga entir)-a 9 kan thlen hnuah 10 (“10”)-ah kan chhiar leh tan a ni. Hetiang pattern hi 15 (“1F”) kan thlen thlengin a kal zel a, chutah chuan 0-ah kan reset leh a, 16 (“20”)-ah kan chhiar leh ta a ni. Hei hi a tir lamah chuan buaithlak takin a lang thei a, mahse tlem tal practice chuan second nature a lo ni tawh ang!';
$lang['Lastly, just like in base 10 (the decimal system), each place value of a hexadecimal number represents a power of 16. So for example, if we had the number 423004 stored as a hexadecimal value:'] = 'A tawp berah chuan base 10 (decimal system) ang bawkin hexadecimal number place value tin hian power 16 a entir a, chuvangin entirnan, number 423004 hi hexadecimal value anga dah ila:';
